		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2013"></a><br><code>sle2013/paper04</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2013</a> paper:</span><br><i>Variability Support in Domain-Specific Language Development</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/EdoardoVacchi.html">Edoardo Vacchi</a>, <a href="../profile/WalterCazzola.html">Walter Cazzola</a>, <a href="../profile/SureshPillay.html">Suresh Pillay</a>, <a href="../profile/BenoîtCombemale.html">Benoît Combemale</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-319-02654-1_5">10.1007/978-3-319-02654-1_5</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2c.html"><span class="tagM">T2C: Variability</span></a><ul><li> The paper’s core problem is handling variability across families of related DSLs to reduce repeated language/tool engineering effort.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> It leverages modularization/composition mechanisms to factor commonality and manage variation points in DSL implementations.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1e.html"><span class="tagL">T1E: Reuse</span></a><ul><li> The approach is motivated by reuse of language concepts and reusable tool support across multiple DSL variants.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> The setting is recurring DSL development, i.e., engineering multiple DSLs in a domain or product family.
</li></ul></li></ul>
